ch.unige.ng.populations
Class CachingPopulation<T extends GlobalIndividual>

java.lang.Object
  ch.unige.ng.populations.CachingPopulation<T>
All Implemented Interfaces:
IGroup<T>, Population<T>, CachingObject, java.lang.Iterable<T>
public class CachingPopulation<T extends GlobalIndividual>
extends java.lang.Object
implements CachingObject, Population<T>

This class defines a population with some caching functions. A cache size is given. The population will keep into memory all the individuals, until there is no more space available.

When individuals are added, the object check if an equivalent object is in the cache. If it does, the object (in memory) will be put in memory. This way can have two advantages:

  • The same individual is present only one time: there are multiple references on it.
  • We can hope that an individual that is in the cache has allready calculated its fitness. The algorithm can maybe go much faster.

The problem is that this cache only works with deterministic fitness. If you want to calculate each time the fitness, this object will not be usefull

The cache will grow if the number of individual are bigger than the limited size. The goal is that the cache has to contain at least the number of individuals in the current and in the next population and some other values. It avoid some border effects. The goal is to be sure that there is at least max(2*currentPop,currentPop+creatingPop)*4./3. This idea is used to be sure that the cache will still work with a increasing population

5 avr. 2005

The cache Size used. The value has to be in the following form: [0-9]+[KMG]

If you want to give 10 MegaBytes to in the cache, you have to write 10M
